Of the ten yield curve inversions back to 1956, the S&P 500 topped out within approximately three months of the inversion more than half the time, or on six occasions - 1956, 1959, 1965, 1973, 1980, and 2000.
The typical pattern is the yield curve inverts, the S&P 500 tops sometime after the curve inverts  and the US economy goes into recession six to seven months after the S&P 500 peaks

The S&P 500 tends to peak 7.3 months (average) or 2.6 months (median) after a 2s10s yield curve inversion. The range of S&P 500 peaks is from 1.6 months (1973) to 21.6 months (2005) after the inversion – a wide range.   https://t.co/vkxbqPR6pL
